{"/service/ndnp/cohi/batch_cohi_baldwin_ver01/data/sn90051006/00414214332/1921011101/0748.xml":{"full_text":"The Idaho Springs Siftings-News\nPublished Every Tuesday and Friday\nLee H. Hoffman and Mrs. Bertha C. Hoffman, Editors\nEntered as second-class matter June 3, 1905, at the |>ostofflce In Idaho Springs, Colorado\nunder the Act of Congress of March 3, 1879.\nOfficial Paper of Clear Creek County\nSubscription, 03.00 Per Year\nProsperity Ahead\nThere is much comfort to be bad\nfrom the statement recently of\nJudge Elbert H. Gary, head of the\nUnited States Steel corporation,\nthe greatest business concern the\nworld has ever produced.\nJudge Gary says a loug period\nof wonderful prosperity is just\nahead of the people of the United\nStates. When he opens his mouth\nhe is in the habit of saying some\nthing and never says a thing un\nless he knows what he is talking\nabout.\nHe has been a wise prophet in\nthe past, because he possesses the\nability to read conditions and pos\nsibilities as they are. There is no\nreason why his prophesy should\nnot be one of wisdom in this case,\nbecause there is no reason why we\nshould not prosper and every rea\nson why we should.\nBanks and financiers generally\nstate that we have passed thru our\nworst period of depression and are\nnow on the up grade. Only the\nrankest kind of pessimism can hold\nus back. And who wants to be a\npessimist when ever, human in\nstinct spurs us on to optimism?\nLet\u2019s demonstrate our faith in the\nreturn of prosperity by recognizing\nthe fact that it is here, and by do\ning our share toward its mainten\nance in this community.\nA proportionate amount of the\nprosperity of the country belongs\nto the people of this community.\nLet\u2019s get all we can and keep all\nwe get. Other communities will\nbe doing the same.\nGovernor Edwards of New Jer\nsey put a bottle of Scotch whisky\nin the cornerstone of a Jersey City\nbank of which he is president. Be\nsides the inexcusable waste, that\nis offering unnecessary temptation\n...Jhank yThosjcAcgt\u2014\nKremmling News.\nOur dear friends of the big city\npress have been caught napping at\nlast. They have neglected to re\ngale us with the information that\nthe Hardings will reside in the\nwhite house after the senator takes\nthe oath of office.\nJudge Gary, head of the United\nStates Steel corporation, the great\nest business concern in the world,\nsays we have a long period of won\nderful prosperity ahead of us.\nBully! Let\u2019s catch up with it.\nIn former days we used to take\nsome of the lurid stories in the big\ncity dailies with a grain of salt, but\nof late we have discontinued the\nhabit. The salt bill mounts up too\nrapidly.\nSome people wag their tongues\nso rapidly their brains are unable\nto keep up. But not you.\nAGAIN\nWe call your attention to\nPasadena Tomatoes\nPoinsetta Peaches\nChase Sanborn\u2019s Seal\nBrand Coffee\nThese brands are superior to all. For\nsale exclusively by\nThe Roberts Bros. Groc. Co.\nSubscribe for Twice-a-Week Siftings-News\nWatson to the Rescue\nThomas B. Watson, the new\nUnited States senator from\nGeorgia, is to introduce a bill in\nthe senate making liberty bonds\nlegal tender. This would put them\non a par with the national currency\nand restore them to at least par\nvalue.\nIf the government ever hopes to\nsell another bond in this country in\ntime of emergency it will do well\nto protect the bondholders now.\nIt requires simply an act of con\ngress to make every one of these\nbonds legal tender. That would re\nquire every person to accept them\nin payment of obligations just the\nsame as currency.\nThey would possess an added\nadvantage even to the small in\nvester, whereas now they are but a\ndespised and depreciating drug in\nthe market.\nIt\u2019s clearly up to our Uncle Sam\nuel, so shrewd in many things, but\nso blind in this, for some of these\ndaj\u2019s he may need the wherewith\nall to again patch his pants.\nAnd the dear and confiding pub\nlic has a disagreeable habit of re\nmembering disagreeable things.\nKeepingeverlastingly at it brings\nsuccess, but a fellow has to be\neternally on the job to keep some\ncuss from reaching in and grab\nbing it away from him.\nAnd still, our gunmen of today\nserve at least one good purpose.\nThey are so numerous no foreign\ncountry would have the temerity\nto tackle us.\nA Kansas undertaker announces\na decided cut in price of coffins,\nbut that does not make them any\nmore attractive as an investment.\nAs president of Mexico General\nObregon is making a great record.\nHo hnsri\u2019t eassed the United States\nonce since he assumed office.\nNo, we have no intention of con\nducting a straw vote to determine\nthe smartest man in town. They\nare all too modest to vote.\nWoman is the brightest jewel in\nthe crown of man\u2014or at least she\nwas before she commenced to vote.\nNow she owns the crown.\nHere\u2019s hoping you all meet with\nunbounded success the present\nyear. And don\u2019t forget to meet us\nafter it comes your way.\nDon\u2019t be downhearted at the be\nginning of this glorious year. All\nthings come to him who waits\u2014\neven death.\nIf we could see ourselves as\nothers see us most of us would pre\npare to look at something else.\nWealth seldom comes unbidden.\nIt don\u2019t get a chance.\nLady Elks Entertained\nRoyally Saturday Eve\nRegardless ot the cold, windy\nweather outside, the interior of the\nElks Home Saturday night was\ncozy and comfortable, and the time\nwas most enjoyably spent. It was\nthe first of the parties this season,\nwhen the ladies were included in\nthe good times, and all who were\nthere, felt grateful to the order for\nthe good times provided.\nThe evening was devoted to\ncards and dancing, five tables being\nin use in the progressive \u201cHigh\nFive\u201d games, while other tables\nwere used lor individual games.\nPrizes were given to the ladies\nMiss Myitle Huddleston being j\nawarded first prize lor holding high j\nscore, haviog won five games out j\nof s x, and Mrs. Lillian Bowden\nreceived the second prize, being j\nfortunate in the drawing when\nfour ladies who bad won four\ngames, \u201ccut\u201d tc see who was to\nreceive the prize. The other three\nwere Mrs. Henry Nimmo, Mrs.Du\nmofat, Sr., and Minnie O\u2019Donnell.\nThe young people spent the time\nin dancing, aud at a late hour a\nsupper, consisting of oyster stew\nor coctail, pickles, cheese, slaw,\ncake and coffee, was served. Every\nthing was well prepared, and the\ncommittee, W. J. Woodward, W.\nA. Keelor, and Oscar Dumont, de\nserves much credit for the \u201ceats\u201d\nand entertainment provided.\nThe ladies are anxious that the\ngood times continue, and will be\npleased if they are permitted to\nhave the hall for an afternoon and\nevening once each month, as is\nbeing talked of.\nJohn Rohner is in Denver on\nbusiness.\n\u2014Drink Ford\u2019s fruit cider. It is\ngood for rheumatism.\nMrs. C. A. Crowe and little son\nare in Denver for a short visit.\nMrs. Elizabeth Gleason was a\npassenger to Georgetown Tuesday.\nSam Lowe of Denver was an\nIdaho Springs visitor Monday and\nTuesday.\n\u2014We have a beautiful library and\nlet\u2019s maintain it properly. See the\nvaudeville t t\nCarl Johnson is in Denver buy\ning leather for his new shoemak\ning establishment.\nIrvan Evans spent Sunday here.\nMr. Evans has a very good posi\ntion with the Publio Market in\nDenver.\n\u2014Make it a merry, melodious,\nmirthful, mystifying, musical mile\nstone in your career. Vaudeville,\nFeb. 7.\nMisses Clara Henderson and\nMattie Shaffer of Denver spent\nSunday and Monday in Idaho\nSprings.\nMildred Jones spent the week\nend with her parents here. She\nhas charge of the Lathrop school\nnear Arvada\nMrs. Grace Williams returned\nSunday to her home in Longmont\nafter a visit with friends here for\nthe week end.\nMiss Etta Merchant, who spent\nseveral days in Idaho Springs, mo\ntored back to Denver today with a\nparty of friends.\nW. B. SaffoTd of Mayfield, Ken\ntucky, came up from Denver to\nspend Sunday with his cousin,\nMrs. Mary O. Allen.\nJimmy Fitzmorris and company\nhave shipped some very fine look\ning ore this week from the Turner\nin the Freeland mine.\nMisses Edith and Grace Clark\nson* returned this week to their\nhome in Denver after a couple of\ndays spent in this city.\nSid Varney left for Golden Mon\nday morning. He expects to take\ncharge of a class in physical train\ning at the School of Mines.\nEugene Conner, who spent the\nholidays with his family in this\ncity, left today for Aguilar, Colo\nrado, where he is employed.\nDOLL HOSPITAL, next door\nto postoffice. Dolls, toys, novelties\nand notions. Twelve years\u2019 expe\nrience. Mrs. H. H. Hansel].\nThe Redmen lodge members are\nplanning for a good time and\n\u201cfeed\u201d in their new quarters at the\nI. O. O, F. hall Thursday night.\nIn Using Long Distance-\nIn placing a call to a distant point, thought should be taken\nof the convenience of the person called, and of others who wish\nto use the line.\nIt isn\u2019t a kind act to place a long-distance call and then leave\nyour telephone before connection is made with the distant person.\nFor instance, you place a call for a busy man in Busyville. Then\nyou leave your office. Meanwhile, the Busyville man is called, he\nanswers, the operator rings your telephone and there is no re\nsponse or she is told you have stepped out. It is not only annoy\ning to the person called, but others who are waiting have been\ndelayed in securing the circuit.\nIf you MUST leave the telephone before the call has been com\npleted, please notify \u201cLong Distance\u201d at which telephone you can\nbe called. This will prevent inconvenience to the person called\nand will conserve the use of long-distance facilities.\nEach subscriber is an essential factor in good telephone service,\nand we will greatly appreciate during this year, as in the past,\nyour doing your part in the use of your telephone, and your\nfriendly attitude towards our efforts to make the service the best\npossible.\nBy the Way\u2014\nAre you taking advantage of our reduced Evening and Night\nRates? Between 8:30 p. m. and midnight, station-to-station calls\n\u2014that is, calls for numbers only and not for a particular person\u2014\nare ONE-HALF the day rate. Between midnight and 4:30 a. m.\nsuch calls are ONE-FOURTH the day rate.\nTRY THESE RATES ON YOUR TELEPHONE\nThe Mountain States Telephone and\nTelegraph Company\nDo More Advertising\nIt is to be regretted that Idaho\nSprings does not receive the\namount of advertising that it de\nserves. People who visit the city\nexpress surprise that it is not bet\nter advertised. More support of\nthe Bureau of Mines and Com\nmerce, and there will be more\nlife among the business men.\nThink of it! A city of nearly\ntwo thousand people, splendidly\nlighted, fine bripk buildings, .the\nbest school system in the state,\ntwo strong banks, surrounded by\nthe richest mining district in the\nstate, less than forty miles from\nthe state capital, churches of every\ndenomination, lodges, hot mineral\nsprings, the finest climate and the\nmost picturesque scenery in the\nworld.\nIt is a little less than a shame\nthat such a city has a Bureau of\nMines and Commerce that wants\nto advertise our resources, and\nthe organization has not the back\ning of every business man in the\ntown.\nMiss Zelma Ball returned Sun\nday evening from Cbickasha, Okla\nhoma, where she has spent the\npast three weeks with her parents.\nMost great men have very little\nto say. That\u2019s one reason why\nthey are considered great.\nThere\u2019s a heap of fun editing a\ncountry paper, but we never have\ntime to enjoy it.\nThis would be a bleak and dreary\nworld if we had no fools to tell us\nof their wisdom.\nSubscribe for the Siftings.\nG. ARKILLS\nChemist and Assayer\nCONTROLS A SPECIALTY\nAt J. J. Elliott\u2019s Old Stand\n1517 MINER STREET\nJAMES UNDERHILL\nMining Engineer\n0. S, MINERAL surveyor\nPhones Forks and Idaho 41\nUkscbsiu Bldg. Ida.ro Synijvo*. Cano\nMRS. GENEVIEVE PEECHER\nNotary Public\nFirst National Bank Phone Idaho 40\nNewsy Notes From\nGeorgetown Vicinity\n(From Georgetown Courier.)\nMiss Edith Swanson returned to\nFort Collins last Sunday.\nMiss Marjorie Kirby returned to\nGreeley the first of the week.\nMrs. F. J. Wood went to Denver\nWednesday to remain for some\ntime.\nMi9s Mellie Wing returned to\nDenver on Monday after speuding\nthe holidays with relatives aud\nfriends.\nMiles Cottingham is out of the\nhospital and improvingright along,\nbut sti 11 supports his misfortune\nwith a pair of crutches.\nClaiming $30,000 in alimony\nfrom her former husband, from\nwhom she was divorced in Clear\nCreek county in 1910, and who\ndied Jan. 11, 1914, Mrs. Carrie j\nRogers has applied to the county\ncourt in Denver for an order al\nlowing her claim against assets of\nthe estate of William Rogers.\nl E S wsriS \u00df s\u00abf LL i pS 4 cosw W-;tan\nrJoauctum K.fcbTLtSS SEX' A PARAMOUNT PICTURE\n\u201cTHE RESTLESS SEX\u201d\nAt Opera House, Thursday and\nFriday, 13th and 14th\nTWO SHOWS EACH NIGHT\nAdults 30 cents Children 15 cents\nSaturday night, the opening of\nthe basket ball season will be noted\nby a game between the high school\nteam and the young men\u2019s class of\nthe Methodist Sunday school.\nNeither team is anticipating de\nfeat. Results later.\nSuch a relief! Ig2l looks just\nlike any other year.\nArthur Curr, E. J. King, and W.\nJ. Kalina returned to St. Thomas\nseminary Monday morning w\u2019here\nthey will continue their study.\nYOUR WANT ADS.\nFOR SALE\u2014Underwood Typewriter in\ngood condition. Pearl Hoban, Sift\nings-News Office.\nIF Yi \u2019U WANT what you want when\nyou want it, try a Siftings-News want\nad. It will pay. tf\nFOR RENT\u2014Furnished rooms for light\nhouse keeping, modern and close in.\n\u2014lOl4 Miner. I ntf\nFOR RENT\u2014Five room modern cot\ntage. 946 Virginia street, Mrs. James\nWeeks. 1-8 It\nFOR SALE\u2014A good gear hoist, Bxio,\nSee 0. H. Walde, i 4-i3t.","height":"19572","width":"14420"}}
